##Diary of the Tehran epidemic area

Micro-signal Globus News

Feature description, worldview provides valuable international information and global stories, with 500 overseas reporting specialists in 76 countries around the world. We only do international in-depth reporting and commentary that you can understand.

Editor's note

This is a life diary written by the author in Tehran, Iran, from February 21 to March 1.

In contrast to other countries, Iran's extremely tense international situation, its fragile economy under years of sanctions and its deeply rooted religious traditions all influence its attitude towards the epidemic. From the night of February 20, when Iran first announced the discovery of a new crown disease in its territory, to March 1, the cumulative number of confirmed cases reached 978 and a number of high-ranking officials were infected. In just 10 days, Iran has gone from ignoring the virus to attaching importance to it, from derision to intense mental change, the epidemic continues to this day.

As of March 5, there were 3,513 confirmed cases in Iran, and the author is still at home in Tehran, waiting for the turning point. Life goes on.

Friday, February 21st. Sunny

Last night, Iran finally announced that there had been two confirmed cases in Qom, and they both died. This is the pace at which hundreds of people become ill, as measured by the death rate of the coronavirus in China.

I was a little nervous at the time, wondering if the government should hold off the next day's parliamentary elections for a few weeks to contain the outbreak. Turning on their mobile phones to watch live Iranian government television news, the state media still encouraged people to take to the streets to vote in parliamentary elections, stressing that it doesn't matter who the candidate is, and that voting is a slap in the face to Americans.

It is a sign of low self-confidence to think about what others think when you are doing your own thing. Perhaps the conservative-controlled Guardian Council was guilty of disqualifying too many reformists, hurting voter enthusiasm.

Kashani, a prominent Internet commentator in the Iranian government, took to twitter to accuse some Iranians of spreading the fear of coronavirus to discourage people from voting and of being "filthy" .

● The twitter account / Network of Kashani, a pro-government commentator in Iran

The regime's credibility may have been damaged by the killing of Sulejmani at the start of the year, when the Revolutionary Guards accidentally shot down a passenger plane, and the government is apparently counting on turnout to save face in parliamentary elections this time around. Not surprisingly, some Iranians put pride ahead of life.

Oh, don't worry about other people's business. On a nice Friday, 800 meters away, at the Cyrus supermarket on Nayeb Road (no one in China would dare call it Qin Shi Huang) , a soldier holds an ak-47 as he walks past a kindergarten, the muzzle of the gun was dangling in the dark.

I gasped and peered into the kindergarten, which turned out to be a regional polling station. It was empty, and a few of the staff were lounging in the Sun. This turnout looks like it's GonNa be a disaster. I wanted to take a picture, but I caught a glimpse of the ak-47. I don't think so.

Big Weekend, the supermarket people are not many, bought two catties of chicken, a fish, a bag of rice. It is also a wonder that rice from Gilan Province, in the north of the country itself, has recently become so cheap that it has bought imported rice from India.

Upon returning home, the Ministry of Health announced that there had been four confirmed cases in Tehran, 18 nationwide and four deaths. Word got back to the parents back home, and they're worried. I told them to take care of themselves.

In the evening, Iran's regional ally Iraq announced the closure of the border with Iran. It seems that the situation in Iran is not optimistic.

Saturday, February 22nd, cloudy

Despite many worries, I gritted my teeth and went to work.

The partner, an Iranian company, arrived in the morning and told his Iranian friends to work at home tomorrow, saying the outbreak was no joke. He thought I was a drama Queen, but I insisted, and eventually he agreed to hire a car to take me to and from work every day.

At noon, my friend went to the court to handle the case, "today, my friend, the deputy attorney general, told me not to be afraid of the virus, " he said cheerfully. "The virus is a rumor deliberately spread by the government, so people would not dare to take to the streets to demonstrate. "

How could he believe such a naive conspiracy theory when he came from a wealthy family with a large villa with a 200 square yard in a wealthy part of Tehran and a fortune in Iran's top 50?

Afternoon take the company car home, see few people wearing masks on the street, Iranians really big heart. But why are the company downstairs several pharmacies all put up signs saying that the mask sold out? Is there a profiteer hoarding? Oh, now I'm a conspiracy theorist. Shame.

In the car, the news showed that the mayor of Tehran's 13th Arrondissement had tested positive for coronavirus. Attached to the news was a picture from the day before yesterday showing him attending a meeting of the Tehran City Council and sitting next to its president, Mosson. Coronaviruses are politically correct, and care for people from all walks of life.

: : At the Coordination Meeting of the Tehran City Council on the 20th, a person wearing a mask in the front row was found to have an infection a day later, to the right of the council president, Mosson, son of the former president's Hashemi Rafsanjani

In other news, two imported cases in Dubai, all Iranian. Yesterday, it seemed that Iraq and Lebanon also had an Iranian import case, Iran seems to become a major epidemic of the rhythm. The export ratio also raises questions about how many people in Iran are sick.

Open Up Wechat and chat with Chinese friends in Iraq, and discuss if Dubai, like Iraq, cut off flights to Iran, considering that the Middle East is the only country with domestic flights under the epidemic, said Emirates, a spokesman for Iran's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, well, then we're GONNA have to fly back to Russia on some lame-ass airline. Then, I searched the Internet for the ultimate experience of a combat nation pilot, and the adrenaline was tingling.

In the evening, watch the official news from Iran. Imam Saidi, the Custodian of the Holy Sepulchre in Qom, the site of the outbreak, opposes the closure of the Holy Sepulchre and the cancellation of Friday services. In his view, the Holy Sepulchre was a place of healing, not infection. In my opinion, how to balance science and religion in the face of the epidemic is a big problem for the Iranian government.

There were 10 new cases today, two in Tehran, 28 nationwide, and five deaths, according to official Iranian government figures. Tell your friends you're not going to work tomorrow.

Sunday rain, February 23rd

The government announced a three-day suspension of primary, secondary and university schools, and public transport and subways began to be disinfected. That's a good sign. Whatever contempt the government may have for the virus, the right policies are already in place.

Friends posted pictures saying that the shelves of Tehran's largest Hyperstar supermarket were empty, as were most of the supermarket shelves in the Middle Class neighborhood on the North Street of the Revolutionary Guard.

It goes against everything I've been feeling in a couple of days -- like a sea of hearts on the streets of Iran. Still, I couldn't resist a visit to my usual butcher shop. Well, there's plenty of meat.

The butcher was introduced to the dumpling food and asked whether veal was better or braised. At last he cut two catties of brain meat and ground it into stuffing and gave it to me. 480,000 rials. I asked him to bring me a chicken breast to feed to the stray cat downstairs for half a million yuan (about 83 yuan) .

Look at you middle-class Iranians, who normally consider themselves cultural elites and social leaders, who constantly criticize the government for corruption and corruption, who speak the language of Baclass, which means "class" , and now there's an epidemic, and you're like a bunch of lowlifes going to the grocery store to get supplies. We in the south city of Iran, ordinary people, usually no culture, in the face of disaster is calm and relaxed, no one snapped up supplies, not only meat shop is complete, there is spare for stray cats to enjoy.

I know every stray cat in that alley. The closest one was a cow cat with a high eq. He would turn his stomach whenever he saw me, and would follow me all the way up the stairs to the house. He would sleep on the carpet when he was full of meat and food, and when he had slept enough, he would meow and open the door and leave, a little "I do not pester you, you do not pester me, we meet again is still a friend" character.

Cows and cats on the rug in the author's house

There is a gray back white-bellied "Xi Xi" , usually squatting in the alley under the grocery store shelf, a saw me pass by meow ground rubbing me meow. I couldn't move my legs, so I went to the concession stand to buy Bacon for her. I doubt she had any secret shop training.

My best stray cat is Mehew, a female with three stripes. She is very introverted, never to strangers to beg for food, coincidentally, I just moved here, the first to feed her. She had a 2-month-old with her, and she was very lively. A month later, on a rainy night, her child died under the wheels of a car. Three days without food or water, she howled at the place where the child had died.

Seeing the heavy rain that night, I thought about leaving her baby in the House for the night and forgot about it because I had too much on my plate. Do not want to read the difference, Human Cat Yin and Yang, the heart of guilt has been difficult to disperse.

Bought Chicken today, saw her in the alley, went over to feed her. Ms. Sarah, the older woman from the alley across the street, was just coming out to feed. She is Mehew's "main breadwinner" (I mostly feed the cow) and was jailed for eight days last year for taking part in demonstrations against Tehran's municipal government for killing stray animals. According to her, after the outbreak, many people think that stray cats can transmit coronavirus, have chased away stray cats, usually many cat people do not feed the cat, coupled with the rainy nights, the little cuties day is very difficult. I promised her I'd take care of Mehew and the other stray cats.

I thought of Mehew's dead child again. Humans are so powerful and indifferent that the driver accidentally makes the mother cat lose her baby. And how fragile the human, coronavirus like Heaven after the Gods Drunk Horse Racing Carnival, the fate of the wheel of how many lives, how many people died of grief!

Monday, February 24th

Stay home for a few days, check twitter, see what's going on. Has Been bombarded today with the aphorisms of high officials.

Rohani: A lot of people die of natural causes, so why blame the coronavirus? Me: surprised look.

Velayati: Coronaviruses are less dangerous than influenza. Me: lost my jaw.

Iranian state TV expert says washing your hands is better than wearing a mask. Me: doubt.

Vice Minister of Health: The virus is not a big deal, at first you can rest at home drinking water to eat vitamins, serious illness to go to the hospital. Me: finally understand why Iranian coronavirus mortality rate is high, you did not count the mild cases!

Vice Minister of Health: Urban Segregation is an outdated policy a hundred years ago. China is not happy about segregation, we are not doing it! Me: that makes a little bit of sense..

Qom's Friday prayer: read the Bible, Hadith, don't get sick. Me: It seems to be a 1300 practice, older than segregation..

The Iranian government is understandably trying to make a harmless gesture about the virus. Iran is now economically depressed, isolated, economically bankrupt, people will seize supplies caused by shortages of social unrest. Economic Protection and absolute control of the epidemic can only be managed at one end. No Quarantine, smooth operation of society, the people eat and work in all normal, but this epidemic to spread.

The outbreak, which centers on Qom, a Shiite pilgrimage destination, has spread through Iran to the Middle East, with three cases imported from Kuwait, two from Bahrain, two from Oman and one from Iraq. Iran began to be isolated. Armenia, Afghanistan, Turkmenistan, Pakistan and Turkey have closed their borders with Iran. As if Turkey were still a little embarrassed, the health minister came out and said hypocritically: "If you had isolated Qom earlier, I would not have closed the border. "

Fatima Masumeh Shrine in Qom. It is considered one of Iran's holiest sites, and every year large numbers of Shia Muslims make pilgrimages to it

There has been a lot of discussion on social media over the last few days about the source of the outbreak. Chinese workers have been quoted in state media, Qom businessmen have been quoted as importing Chinese, Chinese religious students have been quoted as saying, but have been questioned and denied. But in the minds of Iranians, China is the source of the disease, and questions have been raised about why Maján has not stopped flying after the outbreak.

I'm concerned that patient zero is still missing, and that this outbreak may be difficult to contain.

Tuesday, February 25th

Deputy Health Minister Hariri, who claimed yesterday that most patients with the coronavirus can rest at home, posted a selfie today announcing he has the coronavirus and promising to be out of the hospital within two weeks, iran beats virus in a month. He spoke well, with a smile on his face and a deep, rich voice, and did not look like a sick man.

Yesterday, watching him wipe his sweat as he spoke alongside government spokesman Rabi I, I felt something was wrong. But now the most afraid of the people should be Rabi Yi Bar! Standing next to the sick man for half an hour, knowing that someone in China gets sick in 15 seconds!

Went out for coffee with an old Iranian friend. She's a poet, published her own poetry, and now takes a phd every Tuesday.

Coffee shops are still bustling, and no one is wearing a mask. The boss calmly explained that he cleaned the table, kitchen and door handles with disinfectant every hour. The shop assistants also giggled, not caring much about the virus, because "it's the old people to worry about" , while he rented a house in Tehran with his girlfriend, did not go home, and did not infect his elderly parents.

The poet came up to me and said, "look, the virus has come from China. ". But when it comes to the politicians who have been caught, she is pleased that the virus has a "strong sense of justice" and hopes that the imams will all fall ill and the Iranian people will be set free.

Fortunately, the music was on so loud that no one could hear her.

Later, she told me about her class at Qom, where she came into school with her hands disinfected with solid alcohol. Classes are suspended now, and I really want to go on a trip, but my wallet got so thin that I had to stop and go to the gym every day instead. The Gym also has some protective measures, a pair of disposable gloves for each person entering the door, to avoid the spread of the virus.

When I asked her out, I forgot she had a class in Qom. But never mind. Trust your friends. Don't let the epidemic hurt your friendships. Otherwise, what's the point of living through an epidemic if you don't have any friends?

Wednesday, February 26th

Today, the chairman of Parliament's National Interest Committee, Nur al-zawr, also confirmed that he has been infected with coronavirus. In the Selfie, even more dashing than yesterday's Harry Ritchie. The political correctness of the virus continues.

Two days ago, a Chinese girl and her Iranian husband were confiscated by the police in Tehran for hoarding 500,000 face masks. She was accused of profiteering and damaging the image of the country.

A masked passer-by / Internet in Tehran

Details of today's news emerged that the girl had been hoarding face masks before the outbreak in Iran, ready to be sold with her husband to Europe, which was already suffering from the outbreak. Unexpectedly be reported by the neighbor, the police from the sky, hard to buy the goods have been thrown into the water.

With these facts, the matter can be said to be reversed.

For one thing, the couple did not corner during the Iran outbreak. The Iranian government has no right to confiscate their supplies. Second, the couple did not use the outbreak to sell high-priced masks, 500,000 masks were confiscated when they were lying at home. Finally, according to Iran's unwritten law, "all are free within the walls" , the military police have no right to enter private homes. In the name of the epidemic, the powerful departments broke the consensus of officials and people by entering people's homes and confiscating personal belongings, which will have a long-term negative impact on the scale of civil freedom in the future.

Of course, the worst thing about it is the neighbor's snitch. It is true that everyone is a Blabbermouth, a prominent (negative) cultural trait in Iran. The Iranian government has made good progress in its internal counter-intelligence work, thanks to the prevalence of gossip culture. After all, we all live together. We see each other all the time. How can we live together after all?

Iran's whistle-blowing neighbours may be one of the world's most annoying people.

Thursday, February 27th, Sunny

The number of people infected today has jumped by 105. Daily increment breaking 100 for the first time. Not Good. But Mr. Rabi, who had been standing next to the deputy health minister, tested negative for coronavirus!

Given the glowing glow in the selfies of sick executives, I have to ask: Are you faking it? Then told the people got sick nothing, the result of the people continue to Heart in the street do not wear a mask. There's the conspiracy theory again. I'm GonNa do some soul searching.

In the afternoon, a video of leader Ali Khamenei's speech on coronavirus was released and quickly opened.

: : Ali Khamenei's health has also been the focus of attention after the recent death of a consultant with khamenei.ir  pneumonia

You know, every critical period, the leader's speech has a hammer and nail effect, 2009 school wave, the end of 17 anti-system demonstrations, and then this year the pilot plane caused the public protest, as long as the leader to speak out, it means the incident will be quashed.

But the speech was uneventful. Less than two minutes into the speech, Ali Khamenei looked a little tired, but he praised the health care workers and the Minister of Health, hope that the virus as soon as possible.

The Ministry of Health was singled out for praise, and the closure of the city was unlikely to happen. But he didn't say anything specific, because the virus is more sophisticated than the political opposition, and you can't suppress it with guns and armies.

At night, I can't stay at home. Take a cab to the AVA MALL IN UPTOWN, buy an Armani shirt. People take temperature as soon as they come in. There are paper strips next to the elevator buttons. Some of the workers wear masks.

Large public spaces in Tehran seem to be taking the coronavirus seriously, perhaps in the hope of making it easier for consumers to come and spend, perhaps with much fanfare. Can these epidemic prevention measures is afraid to scare consumers, few people in the shopping mall, the usual busy food plaza only a table at dinner.

Came to the second floor Armani store, before the fancy shirt about 700 yuan. I opened my phone, the bank checked the balance in Chaca, I had enough money, but the next thing I knew, if the outbreak got worse and the bank was closed, no one would go to the bank and send me any money?

Forget it. Your stomach is more important than your clothes. Armani's not buying. Go upstairs and have a $20 fruit smoothie.

On the way home in a taxi, I checked my mobile phone, and saw some heartless young people ordering this country to "copy Chinese homework well" . Wuhan and Hubei People's blood and tears in exchange for the control of the epidemic, you do not go to the deceased to repent, but take the deceased's contribution to their own face gold.

Perhaps only the dead of the epidemic -- and, in particular, the medical workers who died -- are entitled to tell foreigners what to do and what not to do, for they have earned their victory.

But they can't talk anymore.

While Iran is culturally conservative, this does not diminish the Persian culture's respect for personal values. Dostoyevsky also said that it was not permissible to sacrifice a little girl to save the world.

I also recommend reading Hawthorne's the scarlet letter and learning how Heist changed the a on his chest from Adultery to Angel.

Friday, February 28th. Sunny

The 41 year old Islamic Republic, which has never stopped celebrating on Fridays, has been canceled across the country. A mass suicide was averted.

In the face of the epidemic, faith has finally given way to science. The Holy Sepulchre, which is open in Qom, is also regularly hand-sanitized. A few days ago, Imam Saidi, who claimed that the Holy Sepulchre could heal the sick, began to urge the people to take the necessary sanitary measures.

So how can the imam restore religious authority in the hearts of his followers after the outbreak? It is often mentioned in scripture that when a city is ungodly, God will send a plague and a flood to destroy it.

However, in the Shia version of the hadith, where the outbreak originated in Qom, the holy city, "three of the eight gates to heaven are in Qom" . Today, Qom is the cause of death and disease in Iran and throughout the Middle East.

Iran's ayatollah will have to step up their research into Sharia law and give religious instructions that are in keeping with the spirit of science and are useful in fighting the epidemic.

Qom, Iran: A worker disinfects a network of religious sites

Saturday, February 29th, cloudy

Turning on his mobile phone this morning, Mr. Kashani, an Internet commentator who had accused Iran of using the virus to discourage people from voting, died of coronavirus infection. The number of confirmed cases in Iran increased by 209 in one day, an increasing rate.

It's raining outside. The air is good. Get dressed, go downstairs, get ready to go to passenger South Station, where the buses and taxis to Qom are, and film people's Daily Lives. The Gate of the courtyard was pulled and the old lady who lived upstairs bumped into it.

A neighbor, an old woman, Gasp to tell me that just 300 meters away from my home in front of the Plaza de la Revolución Cinema Boulevard, an elderly man suspected of coronavirus suddenly collapsed unconscious, was pulled away by an ambulance. When she found out where I was going, she locked the door and warned me, "it's dangerous to do this now. "

History has proven time and again that neighborhood relations matter. Out of respect for her, I went home. The Old Lady, who had laughed at me for making such a big deal out of wearing a mask, was suddenly so cautious that, in the minds of Iranians, the situation did indeed deteriorate.

Cherishing one's life is the expression of one's worldly feelings. I found it comforting to live in an oasis in the middle of the desert, in a very religious part of Plaza de la Revolución, in a building full of worldly, open minded neighbors.

When I searched the Internet for videos of her lying on the couch, I found that the old lady was telling the truth, and that in addition to this case, there were seven other videos of similar patients lying on the floor. The video is the first opposition account released, and do not know whether the video is really because of the coronavirus lying down, but at this juncture to see such a video, the heart of panic.

Sunday, March 1st, moderate rain

A record 385 new cases have been confirmed, threatening to spiral out of control.

I later discovered that the official number of the Chinese Embassy in Iran sent a message last night, advising Chinese in Iraq not to return to Iran without authorization through a third country, and organizing everyone to register their personal information, suggesting that flights would be arranged if necessary to organize voluntary evacuations of Chinese.

Whether to go or not, that's the question.

Most people want to leave, because the domestic epidemic is basically under control, while the situation in Iran is getting worse and worse. Go. You're out of here.

But I'm hesitating.

Back home, perhaps safe (up to 14 days in isolation) , but am I qualified to share in the relief and security of the people of this country who have survived the outbreak? While many terminally ill people in Wuhan and Hubei don't get medicine and get sicker or even die, while people all over the country live in fear and trembling in their homes during the supposedly happy Chinese New Year, while Zhejiang doctors in quarantine were grieving over their beloved cats being forcibly buried by community leaders, I spent my days abroad breathlessly inhaling outdoor air, traveling to shopping malls and playing with stray cats downstairs.

Back home, I will always bow to life, because I am a deserter, not with fellow hardship. I may still be able to drink and jerk off with my best friends, but my soul will be an island forever.

Now, in Iran, the new epicentre of the global epidemic, there may be an opportunity for self-discovery and redemption. If you can stay here, be a part of the epidemic, go through it all, protect yourself, do what you can for your neighbors, and survive, you might even make your first trip home.

But what if I die?

Yes or no? That's still a question.

(editor-in-chief / Zhang Xibei)

Saturday, February 22nd, cloudy

Despite many worries, I gritted my teeth and went to work.

The partner, an Iranian company, arrived in the morning and told his Iranian friends to work at home tomorrow, saying the outbreak was no joke. He thought I was a drama Queen, but I insisted, and eventually he agreed to hire a car to take me to and from work every day.

At noon, my friend went to the court to handle the case, "today, my friend, the deputy attorney general, told me not to be afraid of the virus, " he said cheerfully. "The virus is a rumor deliberately spread by the government, so people would not dare to take to the streets to demonstrate. "

How could he believe such a naive conspiracy theory when he came from a wealthy family with a large villa with a 200 square yard in a wealthy part of Tehran and a fortune in Iran's top 50?

When she found out where I was going, she locked the door and warned me, "it's dangerous to do this now. "

History has proven time and again that neighborhood relations matter. Out of respect for her, I went home. The Old Lady, who had laughed at me for making such a big deal out of wearing a mask, was suddenly so cautious that, in the minds of Iranians, the situation did indeed deteriorate.

Cherishing one's life is the expression of one's worldly feelings. I found it comforting to live in an oasis in the middle of the desert, in a very religious part of Plaza de la Revolución, in a building full of worldly, open minded neighbors.

When I searched the Internet for videos of her lying on the couch, I found that the old lady was telling the truth, and that in addition to this case, there were seven other videos of similar patients lying on the floor. The video is the first opposition account released, and do not know whether the video is really because of the coronavirus lying down, but at this juncture to see such a video, the heart of panic.

Turning on his mobile phone this morning, Mr. Kashani, an Internet commentator who had accused Iran of using the virus to discourage people from voting, died of coronavirus infection. The number of confirmed cases in Iran increased by 209 in one day, an increasing rate.

Sunday, March 1st, moderate rain

A record 385 new cases have been confirmed, threatening to spiral out of control.

I later discovered that the official number of the Chinese Embassy in Iran sent a message last night, advising Chinese in Iraq not to return to Iran without authorization through a third country, and organizing everyone to register their personal information, suggesting that flights would be arranged if necessary to organize voluntary evacuations of Chinese.

Whether to go or not, that's the question.

Most people want to leave, because the domestic epidemic is basically under control, while the situation in Iran is getting worse and worse. Go. You're out of here.

But I'm hesitating.

Back home, perhaps safe (up to 14 days in isolation) , but am I qualified to share in the relief and security of the people of this country who have survived the outbreak? While many terminally ill people in Wuhan and Hubei don't get medicine and get sicker or even die, while people all over the country live in fear and trembling in their homes during the supposedly happy Chinese New Year, while Zhejiang doctors in quarantine were grieving over their beloved cats being forcibly buried by community leaders, I spent my days abroad breathlessly inhaling outdoor air, traveling to shopping malls and playing with stray cats downstairs.

Back home, I will always bow to life, because I am a deserter, not with fellow hardship. I may still be able to drink and jerk off with my best friends, but my soul will be an island forever.

Now, in Iran, the new epicentre of the global epidemic, there may be an opportunity for self-discovery and redemption. If you can stay here, be a part of the epidemic, go through it all, protect yourself, do what you can for your neighbors, and survive, you might even make your first trip home.

But what if I die?

Yes or no? That's still a question.

(editor-in-chief / Zhang Xibei)
